Watanabe Momo was a selfish young girl who always thought only of herself. She had no regard for the feelings of others, and was always looking for ways to satisfy her own desires.

One day, Momo's parents had gone out for the day and left her in charge of the house. They had also left her with a big bag of treats that they had bought for her to share with her friends.

But Momo had other plans. She took the bag of treats and locked herself in her room, where she proceeded to stuff her face with all the delicious goodies inside.

As she ate, she thought of all the fun she was having, and how her friends would be jealous when they found out what she had done. She didn't care that they would be disappointed and hurt by her actions; all she cared about was satisfying her own greed.

But her joy was short-lived. As she continued to eat, she started to feel sick. She had eaten so much that her stomach was beginning to hurt, and she could barely move.

Momo realized too late that she had made a mistake. She had been so consumed by her own selfish desires that she had ignored the consequences of her actions.

She lay on her bed, feeling miserable and alone, regretting the choices she had made. She knew that she had hurt the people she cared about, and that she had only herself to blame for the pain she was feeling.

In the end, Momo learned that being selfish only leads to loneliness and regret, and that true happiness comes from sharing and caring for others. She vowed to never be selfish again, and to always think of the needs of others before her own.

Kenny is a brilliant main eventer in a japanese environment. Looking beyond the obviously stellar technical and athletic ability, his main problem lies with character work and interacting with the crowds. Like everyone says, he's just too goofy and sardonic, as if he was doing a main event heel run ironically ; a good illustration of that being his off-pitch emotivity during the matches. It's just not something that you could take seriously at all, and the general direction of his "character" was god awful. If we consider a match to be a story, then the explicit point of every recent chapter in the kenny omega book became about how good the story itself is presented and not much else, and honestly I genuinely believe that he was too overwhelmed with running the company and too physically banged up to be as invested in his opponents as he was elsewhere. Going back to the japanese point, the walls between kayfabe and shoot are merged into each other in a unique and peculiar way where you were able to work and get away with a whole lot more while keeping the crowd with you, because their investment as fans hits a number of different internal spots than it does in north america. And this latter points directly affecting the direction of what is produced, therefore changing how you approach your work, so to say the least, the japs can buy into your over the top presentation if it still delivers in terms of passion and effort. Not to mention is the gigantic difference in the format.
I don't think Kenny properly wrapped his head around that transition, which could be because of Twitter clouding his vision on what was really coming through to a national tv audience. His initial reputation in and from japan was directly related to his character, whereas his reputation with the smarky PWG-adjacent crowd is built on the "performance". Even when Kenny wrestled, say, Tenzan, he wrestled with the character intending to win. If it were AEW, it would have turned ironic.

posts.com: Here's an interesting topic for debate: Was the big match between Hulk Hogan and Sgt. Slaughter at WM7 a good idea? Many have said that it was wrong for them to play on the Iraq war and to turn Sgt Slaughter into a traitor. posts.name: Anonymous

1995-1996 he was a heel and losing all his matches. His whole gimmick was he had won millions of dollars, but he had turned into a woman abusing psychopath. This led to him being in a feud with Johnny be Bad (Marc Mero) where he lost his wife and money to him.

posts.com:
I think we need to talk about Corporate Kane, and more exactly how much of an underrated kino it is.
It's a genius gimmick, that which the obese smarks watching wrestling could never understand, just ponder it, the demon becoming a business man, wearing a suit, it's a genius social commentary akin to a Dostoevsky novel.
It's a statement on the death of noble ideals, subjugated by the capitalism of the modern world, to the point where even the untamed mythical like demon can be bought for money, it reminds me of The Jungle by Upton Sinclair, though I can see how people might see similarities with the manifestos of Ted Kaczynski and Karl Marx.
There's also the very obvious comparison to American Psycho by Brett Ellis, with the blunt anti materialist message,the sharp contrast of the monster wearing a clean designer suit, but I also see a bit of a Leon Czgolgosz in the performance.
I also feel some Cormac McCartthy influences in the gimmick, the cynical, almost nihilistic even, nature of it, the implication that evil is simply a natural part of life that we must live with, that even something so inhuman and evil is simply another cog in the corporate machine that is modern society.
It's very rare in wrestling to see such an accurate portrayal of modern society, a reflection of the ugly world that we live in reduced to a simple face on television, the fight turning from philosophical to physical, the dominance of the capitalist regime that crushes your soul now in the form of a 7 foot tall monster, and what a monster it is.
I could go on, but I think I made myself clear by now. You need a fairly high IQ to understand the sheer brilliance of Corporate Kane
If you don't appreciate the genius of Corporate Kane you are a simpleton.

posts.com:
While it is true that Corporate Kane was a unique and memorable character, to suggest that those who do not appreciate its supposed depth and philosophical underpinnings are simpletons is not only condescending, but it also vastly overstates the complexity and artistic merit of the gimmick.

First of all, wrestling is a form of entertainment and should not be judged on the same level as literature or high art. To compare it to the works of Dostoevsky or McCarthy is a stretch at best. While it is possible to draw parallels between the character of Corporate Kane and various literary or cultural figures, it does not necessarily make it a "genius" portrayal of modern society.

Additionally, the notion that the character was a commentary on the death of noble ideals or the dominance of capitalism is subjective and open to interpretation. While some may see it as a reflection of the ugliness of the world we live in, others may simply see it as a fun and engaging wrestling character.

To imply that only those with a high IQ can appreciate the genius of Corporate Kane is elitist and dismissive of the diverse range of experiences and perspectives that fans of wrestling may bring to the table.

While Corporate Kane was certainly a memorable and well-done character, it is not fair or accurate to claim that only those with a certain level of intelligence can appreciate it. To do so belittles both the character itself and the fans who enjoy it.

>>8286397
ratio is your download vs upload. a ratio of 1 would equal you uploading 100% of the amount of data you downloaded. If you downloaded 10GB or 300GB you seeded back that same amount to have a 1 ratio. You generally want to have a ratio above a 1. This is achieved by seeding the torrent for many weeks and snagging some late comers.

xwt offers dozens and dozens of freeleech packs that will help you establish a positive ratio while you download the shit you really want. I recommend high traffic megapacks like WWF and WCW ppv collections, or full year packs of companies like NJPW. Remember, you don't have to download every file in those megapacks to generate an upload. For example, I only have 6GB of the entire 588GB torrent of WCW Saturday Night but have gotten over 650GB of upload in its 5 month lifespan.

Generally if you don't seed a 1:1 then having seeded a torrent for 3 days is enough to avoid getting the ire of the mods.

I recommend qbittorrent as a good torrent program, there's some quality of life improvements for the UI over others like utorrent.

xwt has gone invite only for the first time in its 15 years though to look like it's a credible tracker. (it's not, there's not even a bonus point system that's standard for everything) so you might wanna ask a friend or maybe they'll open up registrations for new years
